Python Variables

Variable are used to store and manage data. It is like a container that holds data.
Variable name must start with letter or the underscore character.
Variable name cannot start with number.
Variable name can only contain alpha-numeric character and underscore. [A-Z, 0-9, _]
Variable name are case sensitive (Name, NAME, name different variables)
Variable name cannot be any of the Python keyword.
Example
a = 10   ✓
var = 5  ✓
_var = 5 ✓
var_1 = 5 ✓
1var = 5 ✗

Assigning Multiple Variables to Many Values

Python allow us to assign values to multiple variable in one line.

Example
a, b, c = "Mango", "Orange", "Banana"

print(a)
print(b)
print(c)

Output
Mango
Orange
Banana

Note: Make sure the number of variables matches the number of values, or else you will get an error.

One Value to Multiple Variables
And you can assign the same value to multiple variables in one line.

Example
x = y = z = "Hello"
print(x)
print(y)
print(z)

Output
Hello
Hello
Hello

Unpack a Collection
If you have a collection of values in a list tuple etc. python allow you to extract the values into wariable This is called upacking

Example
Fruits = ["apple","mango","Banana"]
x,y,z = fruits
print(x)
print(y)
print(z)

Output:-
apple
mango
banana


